        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Now for a more detailed git branch example. Let's say I'm in a git repo on branch `my-awesome-feature`, and I set my statusline like this:\n```vim\nset stl=%f%=%.15(\\ 🪾\\ %{%system('echo\\ -n\\ $(git\\ branch\\ --show-current\\ 2>/dev/null)')%}%<%)\n```\nThe intended result on a 50 columns terminal is to truncate the path from the left and the branch from the right:\n```\n<ath/that/will/need/to/be/truncated 🪾 my-awesome>\n```\nand outside of the git repo, the item group should vanish because the `git` command produced no output:\n```\n<ery/long/file_path/that/will/need/to/be/truncated\n```\nCurrently, this doesn't work. The `%<` inside the git item group is processed at the top level and results in truncation from the right, such that the item group is pushed out of sight (same result inside and outside the repo, i.e. the `%<` inside the group affects truncation whether the item group is shown or not):\n```\n/usr/local/very/long/file_path/that/will/need/to/>\n```\nWhen I increase the width of the terminal to 70 columns and I'm inside the repo, I can see the group and how it has been truncated from the left because of `maxwid=15`, before the result is truncated from the right at the end because of the `%<`:\n```\n/usr/local/very/long/file_path/that/will/need/to/be/truncated<wesome->\n```\nWhen I then increase to 80 columns, I can see the whole path, but the branch is still truncated from the wrong end:\n```\n/usr/local/very/long/file_path/that/will/need/to/be/truncated    <wesome-feature\n```",
